 everything that could not be verified. He then explains how the increase in archaeological discoveries and changing archaeological techniques influenced the story of Rome's birth.Grandazzi produces a depiction of Rome's origins that is both up-to-date and provocative. His use of scientific parallels in describing changes in the ways texts were analyzed and his broad familiarity with comparative material make his synthesis particularly illuminating, and he writes with clarity, verve, and wit.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Apr 2024) 0aArchaeology and historyzItalyzRome. 0aArchaeology in literature. 0aExcavations (Archaeology)zItalyzRome. 0aMythology, Roman. 4aHistory. 7aHISTORY / Ancient / Rome.2bisacsh1 aGrimal, Pierre, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aTodd, Jane Marie, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Archive Pre-2000z978311053617140uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978150173126640uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781501731266423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781501731266/original  a978-3-11-053617-1  Cornell University Press Archive Pre-2000b2000  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_CL  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_CL  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles